{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487307"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:05:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:05:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"317"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/317"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.6,0.04,0.09,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"317"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41882"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/317"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"317"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26854"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3565"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11539"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3858"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42056"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41882"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a two month history of increasing fatigue, generalised weakness, low mood, and a weight gain of 5 kg despite no change in diet. She works as a nurse on rotating day/night shifts and has uncharacteristically struggled to sleep between shifts. Her medical history includes recently diagnosed hypertension. Her medications list includes enalapril. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she looks tired and has a full, plethoric face with central obesity. Her pulse is 92/min, blood pressure 150/94 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min and her BMI is 36\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ekg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E.  Examination of her skin shows bruising on her arms and vivid pink striations on her lower abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Midnight salivary cortisol","Low-dose dexamethasone suppression test","Corticotropin-releasing hormone test","Random serum cortisol level","MRI pituitary"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms of generalised fatigue, weight gain and muscle weakness, in addition to insomnia and depressive symptoms are suggestive of Cushing syndrome, further supported by physical examination features of high blood pressure, facial plethora and central obesity with easy bruising and abdominal striae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBiochemical diagnosis of Cushing\u0027s syndrome typically requires at least two cross-confirmatory results among three commonly-used tests: low-dose dexamethasone suppression test, 24-hour urinary free cortisol (ideally 3 separate collections), and/or midnight salivary cortisol. (Midnight plasma cortisol may also be used in circumstances where midnight venepuncture is feasible, e.g. hospital inpatients.)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elow-dose (1mg) dexamethasone suppression test\u003C/strong\u003E is ideal for investigating suspected Cushing\u0027s syndrome for this patient prior to further investigations to determine the cause. It has high acceptability in outpatient settings, and involves the patient taking a 1mg dose of dexamethasone between 11pm and midnight, then attending for a serum cortisol sample at 8-9am the following morning. A cortisol level of \u0026lt;50 nmol/L is the normal physiological response with a functioning HPA axis, and has high sensitivity (95%) and moderate specificity (80%) for excluding Cushing syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMidnight salivary cortisol\u003C/strong\u003E is less appropriate in this case because disrupted circadian rhythms including shift work are known to influence the typical diurnal variation in cortisol levels and reduce reliability of the test. 24-hour urinary cortisol would be an alternative in this case, though as a general point it is important to note that other causes of hypercortisolism (so-called \u003Cem\u003Epseudo-Cushing\u0027s\u003C/em\u003E) can cause false positives; these include pregnancy, depression, alcohol dependence, morbid obesity, and poorly-controlled diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA low-dose dexamethasone test is one of three tests used to diagnose Cushing syndrome, along with serum cortisol test and 24-hour urinary cortisol\u00a0The low-dose dexamethasone test is more appropriate than a 24 hour urinary cortisol test as this patient has presented to her GP and a 24-hour test would be difficult in the outpatient setting. Serum cortisol levels fluctuate throughout the day and hence a \u003Cstrong\u003Erandom serial cortisol\u003C/strong\u003E is an unreliable test of hypercortisolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI pituitary\u003C/strong\u003E and/or the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorticotropin-releasing hormone test\u003C/strong\u003E are potentially indicated once initial testing confirms ACTH-dependent Cushing syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The low-dose dexamethasone suppression test is a reliable investigation for Cushing syndrome.","Midnight salivary cortisol is less useful in the presence of disrupted circadian rhythm."],"references":["Nieman LK. Diagnosis of Cushing\u0027s Syndrome in the Modern Era. Endocrinol Metab Clin North Am. 2018;47(2):259-273. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29754631/","Nieman LK. Cushing\u0027s syndrome: update on signs, symptoms and biochemical screening. Eur J Endocrinol. 2015;173(4):M33-8. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4553096/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26854"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"317"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26854"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-25T21:45:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-26T16:29:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"317"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41882"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co